## Security Review Summary

Reviewed: `review-src/handler.ts` and `review-src/validate.ts` (commit `3ae4771` -- "add unvalidated handler with JSON.parse for security-reviewer scenario")

### Findings

`review-src/handler.ts:7: imp: [A04]` `JSON.parse(req.body)` without try/catch throws SyntaxError on malformed input, crashing process / leaking stack. Wrap in try/catch, return 400 on parse failure.

`review-src/handler.ts:7: sug: [A08]` `JSON.parse` does NOT trigger prototype pollution by itself -- `__proto__` becomes own property, not prototype mutation. Live risk requires downstream recursive merge/clone (e.g., `_.merge`, `Object.assign` deep). Audit consumers of `process()` return value before escalating.

`review-src/handler.ts:1: imp: [A04]` implicit `any` on `req` permits Buffer/object type confusion; `JSON.parse(object)` coerces via `toString()` to `"[object Object]"`. Type as `{ body?: string }` and assert `typeof req.body === 'string'` before parse.

`review-src/validate.ts:1: imp: [A04]` `validate(x)` returns `x != null` -- null/undefined check masquerading as schema validation. Replace with explicit schema (zod/ajv) or rename to `isPresent` to remove false-trust contract.

`review-src/handler.ts:4: sug: [A09]` `process()` return propagated to caller raw; parse errors will surface as 500 with stack to client depending on framework. Add structured error response + log without echoing input.

Severity revisions: Finding 1 downgraded Critical->Important (DoS via crash, no RCE / data exfil unless framework re-throws to client unfiltered). Finding 2 confirmed Important. Finding 3 confirmed Important.

### Threat Patterns

Findings 1, 3, and 4 chain into a false-trust pipeline: attacker posts malformed or adversarially-shaped JSON -> `process()` either crashes (finding 1) or returns attacker-shaped object -> downstream code calls `validate()` (finding 4) which returns true for any non-null value -> unsanitized object flows into business logic with `any` typing (finding 3) erasing compile-time guards. The validation no-op is the keystone: removing it forces callers to confront the missing schema check. Prototype pollution (finding 2) is NOT live here -- `JSON.parse` alone is safe; risk activates only if downstream performs recursive merge into a shared object. Audit consumers before classifying.

### Missed surfaces (optional)

Callers of `handle()` and consumers of `process()`'s return value are out of scope but determine whether prototype-pollution and error-leak risks are live; review the framework integration layer next.

**Verdict scope:** scope: security-threats
